<section xml:id="sec-citations-guide" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Citation Handling</title>
  
  <introduction>
    <p>
      A guide to managing citations.
      This approach supports long-term maintenance and cross-referencing.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-citation-structure">
    <title>Citation Structure</title>
    
    <p>
      PreTeXt supports structured citation management through bibliographies.
      Here's the recommended approach for longevity:
    </p>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-bibtex-source">
      <title>1. BiTeX Source File</title>
      <p>
        Create a <c>references.bib</c> file in your source directory.
        Use standard BibTeX format for all citations:
      </p>
      <listing>
        <caption>Example BibTeX entries</caption>
        <program language="bibtex">
@article{author2024title,
  author = {First Author and Second Author},
  title = {Title of the Article},
  journal = {Journal Name},
  year = {2024},
  volume = {10},
  number = {3},
  pages = {123--145},
  doi = {10.xxxx/xxxxx}
}

@book{authorYear,
  author = {Author Name},
  title = {Book Title},
  publisher = {Publisher Name},
  year = {2024},
  edition = {1st}
}

@misc{websiteAuthor2024,
  author = {Website Author},
  title = {Title of Webpage},
  url = {https://example.com},
  year = {2024},
  note = {Accessed: YYYY-MM-DD}
}
        </program>
      </listing>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-cite-in-text">
      <title>2. In-Text Citations</title>
      <p>
        Use the <c>&lt;cite&gt;</c> tag to reference entries from your bibliography:
      </p>
      <listing>
        <caption>In-text citation example</caption>
        <program language="pretext">
&lt;p&gt;
  According to recent research &lt;cite 
           bib="hestenes1993hamiltonian" /&gt;, the approach 
  works as follows...
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  Multiple sources support this &lt;cite 
           bib="author2024title authorYear" /&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;
        </program>
      </listing>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-bibliography-setup">
      <title>3. Bibliography Setup in docinfo.ptx</title>
      <p>
        Add bibliography configuration to your <c>docinfo.ptx</c> file.
        Add this inside the <c>&lt;docinfo&gt;</c> element:
      </p>
      <listing>
        <caption>docinfo.ptx bibliography configuration</caption>
        <program language="pretext">
&lt;!-- Near the end of docinfo, before closing tag --&gt;
&lt;!-- Bibliography from external BibTeX file --&gt;
&lt;xi:include href="./references.bib" parse="text" /&gt;

&lt;!-- Or: if using publication.ptx --&gt;
&lt;bibliography&gt;
  &lt;bibfile relative-to="source" source="references.bib" /&gt;
&lt;/bibliography&gt;
        </program>
      </listing>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-citation-workflow">
    <title>Citation Workflow</title>
    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-capturing-citations">
      <title>Capturing New Citations</title>
      <p>
        When you encounter a source:
      </p>
      <ol>
        <li><p>Extract full bibliographic information</p></li>
        <li><p>Add entry to <c>references.bib</c> with a meaningful key</p></li>
        <li><p>Use consistent naming: <c>[firstName][Year][keyword]</c></p></li>
        <li><p>Cite in text where relevant</p></li>
      </ol>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-organizing-citations">
      <title>Organizing Citations</title>
      <p>
        <term>By Category:</term> You might organize your <c>references.bib</c> into sections:
      </p>
      <program language="bibtex">
% ========== PAPERS ==========
@article{...}

% ========== BOOKS ==========
@book{...}

% ========== WEBSITES/MISC ==========
@misc{...}
      </program>
      <p>
        <term>Linking to Field Notes:</term> Cross-reference your Field Notes chapter
        where you summarize these sources:
      </p>
      <program language="pretext">
&lt;p&gt;
  See &lt;xref ref="sec-field-papers" /&gt; for my summary 
  of this paper.
&lt;/p&gt;
      </program>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-citation-best-practices">
    <title>Best Practices for Long-Term Maintenance</title>
    
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Consistent Format:</term> Stick to one style (APA, Chicago, IEEEâ€”PreTeXt 
          handles the rendering).
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Meaningful Keys:</term> Use keys that remind you of the source. 
          <c>smith2024neural</c> is better than <c>ref42</c>.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Complete Information:</term> Include DOI, URL, or other persistent identifiers 
          when available. This helps find sources years later.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Verification:</term> Periodically verify that URLs still work and sources 
          are correctly formatted.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Link to Notes:</term> In Field Notes, always summarize the source and link 
          back to where you cite it in Scribing.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Backup Citations:</term> If a source is critical, consider archiving it 
          (e.g., via Archive.org).
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-citation-examples">
    <title>Complete Example</title>
    
    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-bibtex-example">
      <title>Example BibTeX File</title>
      <listing>
        <caption>references.bib</caption>
        <program language="bibtex">
% ========== PAPERS ==========
@article{kutzbrunton2022parsimony,,
  author = {Kutz, J. Nathan and Brunton, Steven L.},
  title = {Parsimony as the ultimate regularizer for physics-informed machine learning},
  journal = {Nonlinear Dynamics},
  year = {2022},
  volume = {107},
  number = {3},
  pages = {1801--1817},
  doi = {10.1007/s11071-021-07118-3}
}

@article{basir2022pinnfailures,,
  author = {Basir, Soroush and Senocak, Inanc},
  title = {Critical Investigation of Failure Modes in Physics-Informed Neural Networks},
  journal = {AIAA SCITECH 2022 Forum},
  year = {2022},
  doi = {10.2514/6.2022-2353}
}

% ========== BOOKS ==========
@book{brunton2022datadriven,
  author = {Brunton, Steven L. and Kutz, J. Nathan},
  title = {Data-Driven Science and Engineering: Machine Learning, Dynamical Systems, and Control},
  publisher = {Cambridge University Press},
  year = {2022},
  edition = {2}
}

% ========== IN COLLECTION ==========
@incollection{hestenes1993hamiltonian,
  author = {Hestenes, David},
  title = {Hamiltonian Mechanics with Geometric Calculus},
  booktitle = {Clifford Algebras and Their Applications in Mathematical Physics},
  pages = {203--214},
  publisher = {Springer},
  year = {1993},
  doi = {10.1007/s11071-021-07118-3}
}

% ========== WEBSITES ==========
@misc{openaiGPT4,
  author = {OpenAI},
  title = {GPT-4 Technical Report},
  url = {https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.08774},
  year = {2023},
  note = {Accessed: 2024-02-10}
}

@misc{musacchio2024hhmodel,
  author = {Musachhio, Fabrizio},
  title = {Hodgkin-Huxely model},
  url = {https://www.fabriziomusacchio.com/blog/2024-04-21-hodgkin_huxley_model/#gating-variables},
  year = {2024}
}
        </program>
      </listing>
    </subsubsection>

    <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-usage-example">
      <title>Using These Citations</title>
      <p>
        In your Scribing section (e.g., Foundations), you might write:
      </p>
      <listing>
        <caption>Citation usage in Scribing</caption>
        <program language="pretext">
&lt;p&gt;
  The Transformer architecture, introduced by Vaswani et al. 
  &lt;cite bib="transformer2017attention" /&gt;, fundamentally 
  changed how we approach sequence modeling. This built on 
  earlier work in sequence-to-sequence models 
  &lt;cite bib="sutskever2014sequence" /&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  For a comprehensive introduction, see Goodfellow et al. 
  &lt;cite bib="goodfellow2016deep" /&gt;.
&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;
  &lt;term&gt;Related Field Notes:&lt;/term&gt; 
  See &lt;xref ref="sec-field-papers" /&gt; for my summary 
  of the Transformer paper.
&lt;/p&gt;
        </program>
      </listing>
    </subsubsection>

  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-long-term-preservation">
    <title>Long-Term Preservation</title>
    
    <p>
      To ensure your citation system survives decades:
    </p>

    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Version your BibTeX file:</term> Keep it in version control (Git) with clear commit messages.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Use persistent identifiers:</term> Include DOIs, ISBNs, and OCLC numbers when available.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Archive important sources:</term> Use <url href="https://archive.org">Archive.org</url> 
          to snapshot web pages and PDFs.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Maintain a local PDF library:</term> For sources you cite frequently, 
          keep local copies in a standardized location.
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          <term>Document decision rationales:</term> In Meta, explain why you chose 
          certain sources and what makes them canonical.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ol>

  </subsection>

</section>
